'''Doula Mouriki''' ({{lang-el|Ντούλα Μουρίκη}}, 1934–1991) was a Greek [[Byzantine studies|Byzantinologist]] and [[art history|art historian]]. She made important contributions to the study of [[Byzantine art]] in Greece.
Doula Mouriki was born in 1934 at Ampelokepi (near [[Aigio]]). She earned degrees in history and archaeology in 1956 from the [[University of Athens]]. After studies at the Sorbonne, she returned to the University of Athens to earn a degree in French literature in 1958. She was hired by the [[National Archaeological Museum of Athens]] and was a research assistant in the [[Byzantine and Christian Museum]] from 1961 to 1965. She attended Princeton University, studying with [[Kurt Weitzmann]]. She earned her MFA in 1968 and her PhD in 1970.<ref name="Dumbarton"/> She was the first woman to earn a PhD from the University's Department of Art and Archaeology.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Books Received|journal=Princeton Alumni Weekly|date=February 9, 2000|volume=100|page=25|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iFbAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA231&dq=%22doula%20mouriki%22&pg=PA231#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
She studied thirteenth-century Cypriot icons and [[Palaeologan]] monument painting in Greece. She wrote many papers, including two papers on Georgian fresco cycles.
She died on 25 November 1991 in Athens, Greece.<ref name="Dumbarton">{{cite journal|last1=Maguire|first1=Henry|last2=Ševčenko|first2=Nancy|title=Doula Mouriki. 1934-1991|journal=Dumbarton Oaks Papers|date=1993|volume=47|pages=xii-xvi|jstor=1291668}}</ref>
